children.subject: Also a 5th year master's student here, and I am pretty sure you cannot backdate a breadth course, only a technical one. There may be some exceptions due to Covid, but I remember that point being emphasized last year. Make sure you double check the rules/requirements for backdating before selecting your classes.
EECS251A has very small differences in having more requirements in the final project but the rest is more or less the same.

@Anon Mouse I know I was given the opportunity to backdate a breadth course when I asked if it was possible. The only caveat is that it couldn't have fulfilled any requirement for undergraduate work like breadth or a double major requirement. May also be a case by case thing. But I believe it is possible.

I am currently a 5th year masters student so here's some info about mezzanine classes and other things.

As Anon Atom said, there is no grad version of EECS 126, sorry :(

EECS 127 does have EECS 227a. I took it this semester and there was no final project for graduate students. The class was exactly the same as the undergraduate version.

Other mezzanine classes in EECS/CS that I am aware of are: EECS 151/251a (not sure if there are differences), EECS152/252a (grad class has a final project and there is some extra grad material), and CS189/289a (grad class has a final project). You can also take Data100/200 (it is cross listed as CS200) for 5th year masters credit which has a pretty chill graduate final project (I took it this semester). I believe that's all of them, but correct me if I'm wrong.

You could always knock out a 5th year masters breadth class if have the time in your schedule anyways. I would highly suggest Stat 140 if you can get in. Stat 134 is also a probability class that will give you a strong probability background. Or just find some easy, fun upper div in some other department and take the GPA boost.
EE226A is usually offered in the Fall semester. You need to search EE not EECS.

261 (the graduate security class) is completely different from 161.

Also, my understanding is that you can't backdate a mezzanine course - you have to take CS189 as an undergrad and CS289A as a grad. You can't take CS289A as an undergrad.

history.content: I'm planning to apply for 5th year masters, and I see that classes from the final semester of undergrad can count toward those masters requirements. I'm done with undergrad requirements but am doing one more semester so that I can take EE126 and CS161, which I think will be useful for me. I know that EE127 also has a a graduate-graded option, 227, which is basically the same except it has a final project. Does EE126 (or 161) have a graduate option? I didn't see it on their website. Moreover, if it did, would I be allowed to take that as an undergrad so that I can use it for grad requirements (given I'm already done with undergrad requirements)?
